1026
00:55:51.388 --> 00:55:55.658
* It's the way
of life, it's the *


1027
00:55:55.692 --> 00:55:58.895
* Law of the night

1028
00:55:58.928 --> 00:56:00.029
* Yeah

1029
00:56:00.062 --> 00:56:02.299
Hey, Charlie!

1030
00:56:02.332 --> 00:56:05.368
I see you've been wounded
in the line of duty.


1031
00:56:05.402 --> 00:56:07.704
I guess we're
not going back tonight.


1032
00:56:07.737 --> 00:56:10.407
Uh, well,
there's--there's no way
to reach you, Charlie.


1033
00:56:10.440 --> 00:56:14.143
My phone's, uh--
it's gone.


1034
00:56:14.176 --> 00:56:16.012
It's very, uh--

1035
00:56:16.045 --> 00:56:17.280
[ chuckles ] It's wet.

1036
00:56:17.314 --> 00:56:20.283
And there's no way
to reach my man Laird,


1037
00:56:20.317 --> 00:56:24.020
you know, the, uh--
the mainland.


1038
00:56:24.053 --> 00:56:28.090
So me and you, we're--
we're--we're here.


1039
00:56:28.124 --> 00:56:29.359
We're--we're stuck here.

1040
00:56:29.392 --> 00:56:31.794
You know, Jared,
if I didn't know better,


1041
00:56:31.828 --> 00:56:33.830
I'd say you'd
fallen off the wagon.


1042
00:56:33.863 --> 00:56:35.898
[ laughing ]

1043
00:56:35.932 --> 00:56:38.167
I almost fell out
of the fucking wagon.


1044
00:56:38.200 --> 00:56:40.703
Ah, Jesus.

1045
00:56:40.737 --> 00:56:42.839
Listen, I'm having dinner
with someone tonight.


1046
00:56:42.872 --> 00:56:45.107
In case you need to reach me,
her name is Rae Blanchard.


1047
00:56:45.141 --> 00:56:47.243
I'm sure Ben knows
where she lives.


1048
00:56:47.277 --> 00:56:48.411
Mm, okay.

1049
00:56:48.445 --> 00:56:50.947
Yeah.

1050
00:56:50.980 --> 00:56:52.081
You know, Charlie,

1051
00:56:52.114 --> 00:56:54.216
I've never
been so sore in my--


1052
00:56:54.250 --> 00:56:56.118
ow, ohh--

1053
00:56:56.152 --> 00:56:58.220
my whole life.

1054
00:56:58.254 --> 00:57:01.057
Oh, but I tell you what.

1055
00:57:03.025 --> 00:57:05.995
I like this place.

1056
00:57:07.397 --> 00:57:11.934
Yeah, me, too.

1057
00:57:11.968 --> 00:57:13.202
Have fun, tiger.

1058
00:57:13.235 --> 00:57:16.739
Sir. Sorry.

1059
00:57:16.773 --> 00:57:17.907
Be good.

1060
00:57:19.108 --> 00:57:20.310
[ knock on door ]

1061
00:57:20.343 --> 00:57:21.878
Yeah, come in.

1062
00:57:21.911 --> 00:57:23.446
Hey.
Hey.


1063
00:57:23.480 --> 00:57:25.515
Wow, nice.

1064
00:57:25.548 --> 00:57:26.516
Thank you.

1065
00:57:26.549 --> 00:57:28.217
Could you open
that bottle?


1066
00:57:28.250 --> 00:57:29.251
Sure.

1067
00:57:29.286 --> 00:57:33.089
So, how's
your assistant?


1068
00:57:33.122 --> 00:57:35.024
Well marinated, I'd say.

1069
00:57:35.057 --> 00:57:36.293
[ chuckles ]
Glasses?


1070
00:57:36.326 --> 00:57:39.061
Uh, second cupboard.
Where's he staying?


1071
00:57:39.095 --> 00:57:43.333
Uh, he's staying
at Matty's with a young man
named, uh, Ben.


1072
00:57:43.366 --> 00:57:45.201
Yeah.
Matty always steps up.


1073
00:57:45.234 --> 00:57:47.904
She took him in
a few years ago.


1074
00:57:47.937 --> 00:57:50.907
He was raised
in foster homes
and badly abused.


1075
00:57:50.940 --> 00:57:52.909
He's actually
a really sweet kid


1076
00:57:52.942 --> 00:57:56.446
and a wonderful
portrait artist,
a real prodigy.


1077
00:57:56.479 --> 00:58:00.417
I thought that
he was, uh, the stern man
on one of the lobster boats.


1078
00:58:00.450 --> 00:58:02.419
He does that as well
to get a closer feel


1079
00:58:02.452 --> 00:58:04.354
for the lives
of the fishermen.


1080
00:58:04.387 --> 00:58:06.222
Cheers.
[ glasses clink ]


1081
00:58:06.255 --> 00:58:08.190
[ soft music playing ]

1082
00:58:12.895 --> 00:58:14.431
The old flake yards.

1083
00:58:14.464 --> 00:58:17.834
In those days, they'd cure
the codfish in the sun.


1084
00:58:17.867 --> 00:58:21.203
Of course, there aren't
any cod left anymore.


1085
00:58:21.237 --> 00:58:22.572
What are you gonna do
if the grounds


1086
00:58:22.605 --> 00:58:24.474
are opened up
to year-round fishing?


1087
00:58:24.507 --> 00:58:26.443
Fight it with
every means we have.


1088
00:58:26.476 --> 00:58:28.378
Got some
pretty high-powered
lobbying help.


1089
00:58:28.411 --> 00:58:30.313
Yeah,
and we don't have it.


1090
00:58:30.347 --> 00:58:31.848
Even hiring
a local lawyer


1091
00:58:31.881 --> 00:58:34.484
went against the grain
of the people out here.


1092
00:58:34.517 --> 00:58:36.353
The number of those
who want to stay and fight


1093
00:58:36.386 --> 00:58:38.421
grows smaller every day.

1094
00:58:38.455 --> 00:58:41.257
Many are already resigned
to leaving the island.


1095
00:58:51.468 --> 00:58:53.436
[ knock on door ]
Come in.


1096
00:58:55.505 --> 00:58:57.507
I'm afraid I
got some bad news.


1097
00:58:57.540 --> 00:58:58.875
RAE: What happened?

1098
00:58:58.908 --> 00:59:00.543
Well, I
was listening
to the radio,


1099
00:59:00.577 --> 00:59:02.612
and apparently
some congressional
committee


1100
00:59:02.645 --> 00:59:04.381
is having
a special meeting
down there


1101
00:59:04.414 --> 00:59:06.616
to decide on
whether to expel you
from Congress


1102
00:59:06.649 --> 00:59:09.352
for disgracing
the House of
Representatives.


1103
00:59:09.386 --> 00:59:11.488
Something about
an Nazi salute


1104
00:59:11.521 --> 00:59:14.824
and desecration
of the Pledge
of Allegiance.


1105
00:59:18.561 --> 00:59:22.231
So much for exercising
my First Amendment rights.


1106
00:59:22.264 --> 00:59:24.901
Did you do that?

1107
00:59:24.934 --> 00:59:26.469
It's a long story, Sherm.

1108
00:59:29.071 --> 00:59:30.307
Well, they want you
down there


1109
00:59:30.340 --> 00:59:31.641
first thing
Monday morning.


1110
00:59:31.674 --> 00:59:34.344
Should I tell
your assistant?


1111
00:59:34.377 --> 00:59:37.280
No. No, I'd rather
tell him myself. Thanks.


1112
00:59:37.314 --> 00:59:38.515
Okay.

1113
00:59:45.187 --> 00:59:46.956
What is he
talking about?


1114
00:59:49.326 --> 00:59:53.029
The artist really
captured ol' Matty, huh?


1115
00:59:53.062 --> 00:59:56.032
Jesus.

1116
00:59:56.065 --> 00:59:58.435
She's gay, right?

1117
00:59:58.468 --> 00:59:59.636
She's gotta be gay.

1118
00:59:59.669 --> 01:00:01.338
I mean, not that I have--

1119
01:00:01.371 --> 01:00:03.373
I have
anything against that.
I don't, personally.


1120
01:00:03.406 --> 01:00:06.609
It's not a big deal
to me, but, uh,


1121
01:00:06.643 --> 01:00:08.210
she scares me
a little bit,


1122
01:00:08.244 --> 01:00:10.547
you know?
She's mannish.


1123
01:00:10.580 --> 01:00:14.484
I'm just saying
I wouldn't want to,
uh, run into her


1124
01:00:14.517 --> 01:00:16.986
in a dark alley.
You know what I mean?


1125
01:00:17.019 --> 01:00:19.956
Heard you talking
about that painting.


1126
01:00:19.989 --> 01:00:21.257
Um, yes.

1127
01:00:21.291 --> 01:00:23.125
The painting
is very good.


1128
01:00:23.159 --> 01:00:24.994
It's very good.
I was wondering,


1129
01:00:25.027 --> 01:00:27.196
uh, you know,
who the artist was.


1130
01:00:27.229 --> 01:00:29.366
You're sitting
right next to him.


1131
01:00:30.500 --> 01:00:32.034
You?

1132
01:00:32.068 --> 01:00:33.503
You painted that?

1133
01:00:34.537 --> 01:00:36.706
Yeah.

1134
01:00:36.739 --> 01:00:38.174
Wow.

1135
01:00:38.207 --> 01:00:39.542
Ben, that's amazing.

1136
01:00:39.576 --> 01:00:41.243
You should
be really proud
of yourself.


1137
01:00:41.278 --> 01:00:42.979
Thank you.

1138
01:00:43.012 --> 01:00:45.181
Well, cheers.

1139
01:00:48.150 --> 01:00:50.152
Full of mystery,
huh?


1140
01:00:52.121 --> 01:00:55.658
So, what are
you gonna do?


1141
01:00:55.692 --> 01:01:01.431
Go back and deal with it,
I guess, but not tonight.


1142
01:01:01.464 --> 01:01:06.268
Tonight I just want
to have dinner.


1143
01:01:06.303 --> 01:01:08.371
You're not a neo-Nazi,
are you?


1144
01:01:08.405 --> 01:01:09.639
[ laughs ] No.

1145
01:01:09.672 --> 01:01:11.107
I was making a point,

1146
01:01:11.140 --> 01:01:13.009
and it was taken
out of context.


1147
01:01:13.042 --> 01:01:14.411
I understand.

1148
01:01:14.444 --> 01:01:17.246
Thank you.

1149
01:01:17.280 --> 01:01:20.283
You remember telling me
that visitors who come here


1150
01:01:20.317 --> 01:01:21.684
need a few days
to slow down


1151
01:01:21.718 --> 01:01:23.520
to the rhythm
of the sea and the tides?


1152
01:01:23.553 --> 01:01:24.287
Mm-hmm.

1153
01:01:28.157 --> 01:01:30.960
I haven't slowed down
for 18 years.


1154
01:01:32.462 --> 01:01:35.698
Is that how you lost
your marriage?


1155
01:01:35.732 --> 01:01:37.434
Well, in spite
of what my ex-wife thinks,


1156
01:01:37.467 --> 01:01:39.336
it wasn't because
of the perks of the job.


1157
01:01:39.369 --> 01:01:43.373
I knew what to expect
when I went down there.


1158
01:01:43.406 --> 01:01:46.576
You get elected
to Congress, and suddenly
your jokes are funny.


1159
01:01:46.609 --> 01:01:50.280
You discover that you're
God's gift to women,
all the wrong women.


1160
01:01:50.313 --> 01:01:54.150
You get nonstop flattery
from people who all want
something from you,


1161
01:01:54.183 --> 01:01:57.119
but those things were
never a problem for me.


1162
01:01:57.153 --> 01:01:59.322
Then what was it?

1163
01:02:03.393 --> 01:02:06.228
It was this need...

1164
01:02:08.064 --> 01:02:11.167
a need that became
the most compelling thing
in my life...


1165
01:02:13.135 --> 01:02:16.473
more important than my wife
or our marriage or...


1166
01:02:19.208 --> 01:02:20.209
You got kids?

1167
01:02:21.378 --> 01:02:22.379
No.

1168
01:02:22.412 --> 01:02:24.113
I'd still like to.

1169
01:02:24.146 --> 01:02:28.184
Well, that superseded
even them


1170
01:02:28.217 --> 01:02:30.186
and everything else
in my life.


1171
01:02:30.219 --> 01:02:32.221
I don't understand.

1172
01:02:32.254 --> 01:02:35.792
When I got out
of the Marine Corps,


1173
01:02:35.825 --> 01:02:39.228
I felt like I was living
on borrowed time.


1174
01:02:39.261 --> 01:02:43.533
If I didn't accomplish enough
in a given day or week,


1175
01:02:43.566 --> 01:02:49.539
it was like falling behind
in my whole reason
for having survived,


1176
01:02:49.572 --> 01:02:54.511
and I was one day closer
to dying without having
made a difference.


1177
01:02:54.544 --> 01:02:59.716
Hey, maybe you have made
a difference, Charlie.


1178
01:02:59.749 --> 01:03:03.720
Maybe it's just time
to hang up your armor.


1179
01:03:05.888 --> 01:03:08.124
Not that easy.

1180
01:03:08.157 --> 01:03:09.392
Of course it is.

1181
01:03:09.426 --> 01:03:11.361
[ chuckles ]

1182
01:03:11.394 --> 01:03:14.564
Well, not right now.

1183
01:03:16.132 --> 01:03:18.668
Wow, you're
an amazing artist.


1184
01:03:18.701 --> 01:03:22.639
Ben, you really--
You are, man.


1185
01:03:22.672 --> 01:03:23.606
You're great.

1186
01:03:25.408 --> 01:03:27.710
Do you think
I could do one of you?


1187
01:03:27.744 --> 01:03:29.746
What?

1188
01:03:29.779 --> 01:03:31.514
Yeah.

1189
01:03:32.882 --> 01:03:34.684
[ chuckles ]

1190
01:03:36.218 --> 01:03:37.387
Yeah.

1191
01:03:37.420 --> 01:03:39.622
Yeah.
I would be honored.


1192
01:03:39.656 --> 01:03:41.391
What do I
need to do?


1193
01:03:41.424 --> 01:03:44.461
Just, uh, sit on the bed.

1194
01:03:47.397 --> 01:03:48.465
Okay.

1195
01:03:48.498 --> 01:03:49.499
You got it.

1196
01:03:49.532 --> 01:03:52.168
[ laughs ]

1197
01:03:52.201 --> 01:03:53.336
Thank you.

1198
01:03:54.471 --> 01:03:55.772
Wow.

